      <div type="book">
        <linkGrp type="notes"/>
        <div n="971-S899" type="poem"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1">By Mr, S──g,</l></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-971-S899-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-1"><hi rend="display-initial">D</hi>EAR Sir since in Cruxes and Puns, you and I deal,</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-2"> Pray tell me, why is a Woman a <hi rend="underline">Sieve</hi> and a <hi rend="underline">Riddle</hi>.</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-3"> 'Tis a Thought that came into my Noddle this Morning,</l><l n="4" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-4"> In Bed as I lay Sir a tossing and turning.</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-5"> You'll find if you read but a few of your Histories,</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-6"> All Women as <hi rend="underline">Eve</hi>, all Women are Mysteries.</l><l n="7" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-7"> To find out this <hi rend="underline">Riddle</hi>, I know you'l be eager,</l><l n="8" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-8"> And make every one of the Sex a Bell-phagor.</l><l n="9" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-9"> But that will not doe, for I mean to come-mend 'em,</l><l n="10" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-10"> I swear without jest, I an honour intend 'em.</l><l n="11" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-11"> But to tell you a thing that wants Interpretation,</l><l n="12" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-12"> What name for a Maid, was the first Man's Damnation.</l><l n="13" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-13"> A <hi rend="underline">Damsel-Adam's-Hell</hi>, O! there I have hit it,</l><l n="14" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-14"> Just as you conceiv'd it, just so have I writ it.</l><l n="15" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-15"> But now from henceforwards I'l make you to know it,</l><l n="16" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-16"> That now I'm your <hi rend="underline">Ph<unclear>oe</unclear>bus</hi>, and you are my <hi rend="underline">Poet</hi>.</l><l n="17" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-17"> The reason I send you these Lines of Rhymes double,</l><l n="18" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-18"> Is meerly thro' Pity to save you the Trouble</l><l n="19" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-19"> Of thinking 2 hours for a Rhyme as you did last,</l><l n="20" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-20"> When your <hi rend="underline">Pegasus</hi> canter'd in triple and rid fast.</l><l n="21" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-21"> As for my little Nag which I keep at <hi rend="underline">Parnassus</hi>,</l><l n="22" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-22"> With <hi rend="underline">Ph<unclear>oe</unclear>bus</hi>'s Leave to run with his Asses,</l><l n="23" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-23"> He goes, slow, and sure, and he never is jaded,</l><l n="24" xml:id="spp-971-S899-line-24"> Whilst you fiery Steed is whipp'd, spur'd, Bastinaded.<gap/></l></lg></div>
      </div>
